postcontent:
It was just mounted yesterday afternoon but never fired. The gas block barrel roll pin and the muzzle brake have never even been installed. Unfortunately I own a recant suppressor and I decided I don't want to take off the handguard every time I want to use the QD on my can. http://www.midwayusa.com/product/REDACTED/advanced-armament-co-aac-ar-15-pistol-barrel-assembly-300-aac-blackout-1-in-7-twist-chrome-moly-matte-with-low-profile-gas-block?cm_vc=ProductFinding

This Advanced Armament Co (AAC) AR-15 Pistol Barrel Assembly is perfect for the shooter who wishes to build or convert an AR-15 to chamber the new 300 AAC Blackout round in order to take advantage of its unique ballistic characteristics. The barrel is finished inside and out with a highly durable and corrosion resistant Black Nitride, a treatment that produces an extremely hard, slick surface on the steel that resists carbon adhesion for easier cleaning and maintenance. The Nitride process converts the steel's surface without any build-up, retaining all of the benefits of traditional chrome lining without suffering the accuracy degradation commonly encountered with it due to the uneven application of chrome inside a barrel's bore.

The 9" and 12.5" barrel each feature a 1 in 7" twist and is threaded 5/8"-24 at the muzzle. These barrels include the 51T Flash Hider designed to effectively eliminate muzzle flash and works in conjunction with AAC's improved ratchet mount sound suppressors. It utilizes a pistol length gas system and is compatible with most subsonic and supersonic ammunition, with or without a silencer in place. However, some subsonic ammunition may not always cycle reliably under adverse conditions or in a severely fouled firearm without a sound suppressor attached to provide extra backpressure. Barrel assembly includes a pistol gas tube, low profile steel gas block, barrel extension and locator pin. Requires barrel nut for installation (not included).

title: For Sale:  CZ75 Pcr 9mm Double Action/Single Action
postcontent:
The CZ75 PCR 9mm is a variant of the well-respected CZ 75 Double Action/Single Action line, but with a lighter alloy frame and frame mounted de-cocking lever. It's shorter in height than the standard CZ75 for ease of carry and has a fantastic grip feel. It comes in the factory box with two magazines and all the paperwork CZ provides.

I've fired approximately 100 rounds and it worked fine. It's almost LNIB (Like New In Box), except for normal wear for operation.

The double action/single action is a great choice and is done well in this pistol. The first trigger pull is a little harder than my Gen4 Glock, but every other trigger pull is much easier - it feels like cheating. Also, this has a quality barrel and the slide sits inside the receiver rails instead of outside as other pistols have it - it makes for a very accurate pistol and a low barrel centerline. It's a fine pistol, just made for carry. 

I'm retired military, and this is better than what they gave me to carry on active duty.

Three day non-firing inspection. Buyer pays return shipping and fees.

title: For Sale:  Velo-Dog; pocket revolver
postcontent:
I’m offering for sale (cash only) a small pocket revolver that is often referred to as a Velo-Dog. This type of pistol was originally created as a defense for cyclists against dog attacks in Europe.

This particular pistol was brought back from Europe by my dad at the conclusion of WWII.  I have not used the gun but it appears that the firing action works properly. The folding trigger allows for ease in getting pistol in and out of one’s pocket. I’m told that it was made in Belgium prior to WWII.  While it would be a challenge to find the original ammo I learned at a local gun show this week that it would be equivalent to Colt .32 short ammunition. 

As I attempted to show in the photos it has rust around the edges of the nicely checkered grip and on the back spine of the grip. It would be a darn handsome pistol if re-chromed. I can send additional  photos for more detail.

There is considerable information on the web regarding the history of this type of pistol and choices of ammo.
